WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.000
Hello everyone, my name is Rahmat Akintola and I'm honoured to introduce our speaker

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:22.160
for today, Isabel Zimmerman. Isabel is a senior software engineer at PositPBC with a wealth

00:00:22.160 --> 00:00:30.440
of experience in building Python open source data science tools. Isabel is an emeritus

00:00:30.440 --> 00:00:37.200
editor-in-chief at PyOpenSci. Today, Isabel will be sharing insights on making graphics

00:00:37.200 --> 00:00:44.880
user interface data exploration reproducible with Python. I am sure you'll find Isabel's

00:00:44.880 --> 00:00:50.000
talk insightful. Please join me in welcoming Isabel Zimmerman.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:55.799
Hi there. I'm Isabel Zimmerman. I'm a senior software engineer. I'm also a very big cookie

00:00:55.799 --> 00:01:01.279
fan. I love to make them. I love to eat them. I grew up in the kitchen with my mom and she

00:01:01.279 --> 00:01:06.839
would tell me how long to soften the butter and how much cocoa to add and when to take

00:01:06.839 --> 00:01:11.000
the finished product out of the oven. When I moved out of my family home and started

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:15.959
hosting on my own, when my friends would ask me for a recipe, I had to just tell them that

00:01:15.959 --> 00:01:22.239
I measured from the heart. Using a graphic user interface tool for cleaning data is a

00:01:22.239 --> 00:01:27.440
little bit like baking without having a recipe. It works really well for one person, but the

00:01:27.440 --> 00:01:32.160
second that you need to share or reproduce your results, things get tricky. The details

00:01:32.160 --> 00:01:37.320
matter and without writing them down, good luck getting the same cookies twice. I mean,

00:01:37.320 --> 00:01:41.959
we've all been there. You're exploring a data set and you reach for the GUI tool because

00:01:41.959 --> 00:01:48.040
it's just easier. You click, you filter, you visualize. But then someone asks, you

00:01:48.040 --> 00:01:51.959
know, how did you get these results? And you realize it's really hard to reproduce what

00:01:51.959 --> 00:01:57.959
you just did. Today, I want to talk about how we can bridge this gap between the ease

00:01:57.959 --> 00:02:05.000
of GUI tools and the rigor of reproducible code. So, GUI-based data analysis tools are

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:09.880
incredibly appealing. There's something intuitive about, you know, pointing and clicking. You

00:02:09.880 --> 00:02:15.479
get immediate visual feedback as you explore your data. And maybe most importantly, it

00:02:15.479 --> 00:02:22.119
really lowers the barrier to entry to explore data. You don't need to remember exact function

00:02:22.119 --> 00:02:28.119
names or syntax. It makes data exploration way more accessible to more people, which

00:02:28.119 --> 00:02:36.360
is fundamentally a good thing. But here's the problem. Reproducibility is

00:02:36.360 --> 00:02:42.279
extremely important in data science. If you're doing academic research, if you're doing business

00:02:42.279 --> 00:02:46.440
analytics, or you're building a model, someone needs to be able to recreate your work.

00:02:47.080 --> 00:02:52.520
Your collaborators need to understand what you did. And future you, six months from now,

00:02:52.520 --> 00:02:57.240
when you can't remember why you had made certain decisions, really needs that documentation of

00:02:57.240 --> 00:03:04.119
having a script to reproduce your results. Think about it like a recipe. When you make

00:03:04.119 --> 00:03:08.679
cookies from scratch, you can write down the recipe so you can make it again, you can teach

00:03:08.679 --> 00:03:13.320
it to others, and you can tweak it and improve it. Reproducibility isn't just something that's

00:03:13.320 --> 00:03:20.360
nice to have. It's essential. And so, we've been living with this false choice. You know,

00:03:20.360 --> 00:03:27.160
you can either have this easy-to-use GUI tool, or you can have reproducible code-based workflows,

00:03:27.160 --> 00:03:33.559
but not both. Things like Excel are easier, but harder to reproduce. Things like Jupyter

00:03:33.559 --> 00:03:40.119
Notebooks are really reproducible, but have a steeper learning curve. But what if we didn't

00:03:40.119 --> 00:03:46.520
have to choose? What if we could have the ease of a GUI that automatically generates reproducible

00:03:46.520 --> 00:03:53.559
code for everything you do? That's the solution I want to show you today. Automated code generation

00:03:53.559 --> 00:03:59.080
from UI interactions. This is sort of like your kitchen helper that not only is going to weigh

00:03:59.080 --> 00:04:04.279
your ingredients, but automatically write down the recipe as you go. This is a project that I

00:04:04.279 --> 00:04:09.399
worked on and built for the Positron IDE, and it has really interesting implications for other

00:04:09.399 --> 00:04:18.119
Python projects. Let's get into a demo. So, I'm going to be using the Positron IDE to do a little

00:04:18.119 --> 00:04:24.040
bit of data analysis. So, first, I'm going to import the pandas package, and I'm going to use

00:04:24.040 --> 00:04:33.880
this to read in a CSV that has a bunch of recipes. I can use this button to view our data in our GUI

00:04:33.880 --> 00:04:43.880
explorer. So, we can see here that we've got 14,000 rows, 16 columns. Here's all of the columns here

00:04:43.880 --> 00:04:49.559
with a little bit of information about them. Let's say I'm looking for a recipe for friends tonight.

00:04:50.519 --> 00:04:56.359
So, maybe I want to have something that has ingredients that contains chocolate chips.

00:04:59.079 --> 00:05:04.600
I can apply this filter, and now I can see in my ingredients column, all of these will have the

00:05:04.600 --> 00:05:11.480
string value of chocolate chips. Maybe this is also something that I need to make for tonight,

00:05:11.480 --> 00:05:16.920
after work today. So, let's make sure that the total time to prepare this recipe is less than

00:05:17.320 --> 00:05:25.959
or equal to 60 minutes. Now, this seems to be a good set of options. Now, I only have 250,

00:05:25.959 --> 00:05:31.799
but I really am not going to make 250 desserts. I only need one. So, to find the very best one,

00:05:32.679 --> 00:05:39.880
let's maybe sort by the average rating. So, we want the top rated recipes, and maybe also see

00:05:39.880 --> 00:05:47.880
which ones have the most ratings. So, I have the highest rated recipes with the most total ratings

00:05:47.880 --> 00:05:56.359
that take less than 60 minutes to make, and contain chocolate chips. Looks like banana bread

00:05:56.359 --> 00:06:04.040
mug cake in a minute is our winner today. Now, this was a simple GUI type interface

00:06:04.040 --> 00:06:09.480
to interact with this dataset. Now, I'm going to be using this special convert to code button

00:06:10.359 --> 00:06:16.119
to actually generate all of these filters in Pandas. I can copy it right here,

00:06:17.079 --> 00:06:25.640
and if I want to, I can run this code in my Python terminal, and I can see it still has the same 250

00:06:25.640 --> 00:06:33.079
rows and 16 columns that we saw in our GUI interface, and if we see the top set of data

00:06:33.079 --> 00:06:38.679
is, again, our banana bread mug cake in a minute. So, that means I can copy and paste

00:06:38.679 --> 00:06:43.640
this code into a Python script, I can share it with others, and it was automatically generated

00:06:43.640 --> 00:06:53.640
from the GUI interface in the data explorer in Positron. So, now that you've seen it in action,

00:06:53.640 --> 00:06:59.320
let's talk about how this actually works under the hood. So, the first thing that we need to do

00:06:59.320 --> 00:07:06.519
is use the UI to capture what the user is doing. In Positron's case, the front end is

00:07:06.519 --> 00:07:13.000
built with TypeScript and React, but actually, all of this is interacting with an iPy kernel

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:18.760
instance that's running in that console. So, whenever we click a filter button, enter a value,

00:07:18.760 --> 00:07:26.839
select a column, all of these interactions are sent to the Python runtime via Jupyter comms

00:07:26.839 --> 00:07:32.600
and iPy kernel. So, actually, every single time I add a filter, I get some sort of information,

00:07:33.239 --> 00:07:40.200
like the column name and type display and the condition and the parameters. So, I get to see

00:07:40.200 --> 00:07:48.200
that I'm looking for columns that have chocolate chips inside them. This is all sent through JSON,

00:07:48.200 --> 00:07:56.359
so I'm able to intercept this information and act upon it in Python. So, this conversion layer

00:07:56.359 --> 00:08:03.079
is all written in Python. It ingests all the information, all that JSON that we got from the

00:08:03.079 --> 00:08:09.320
Jupyter comm, and it puts it into these code templates. These templates are just classes

00:08:09.320 --> 00:08:15.239
that do a bit of string manipulation, as well as delegating different tasks to a Pandas or

00:08:15.239 --> 00:08:22.839
a Polars back end, depending on what type of data frame the user is using. So, it's possible to do

00:08:22.839 --> 00:08:29.880
this sort of code conversion, because the Positron IDE has these Jupyter comms that have the really

00:08:29.880 --> 00:08:36.359
structured input and output with very rich information, and also because the Pandas and

00:08:36.359 --> 00:08:44.280
Polars data frame libraries have very modular ways to put together the filters and sorts.

00:08:44.919 --> 00:08:49.960
So, we can see here the code that we generated earlier. You can see there's something called a

00:08:49.960 --> 00:08:55.719
filter mask, which we're using to filter our data frame to have different ingredients. And

00:08:55.719 --> 00:09:02.119
if we go through each part of the filter mask, we can see that we're using the data frame name

00:09:02.119 --> 00:09:09.080
of all recipes, a certain column of ingredients, and then an operation. In this case, the operation

00:09:09.080 --> 00:09:15.559
is that the column has a string that contains chocolate chips. It's not case sensitive,

00:09:15.559 --> 00:09:22.039
and it doesn't include NAs. We can also see where we filtered for greater than or less than or equal

00:09:22.039 --> 00:09:30.599
to 60 minutes. Again, we have the very structured data frame name, data frame column, and some sort

00:09:30.599 --> 00:09:37.159
of operation. This maps really well to the information that we're getting from that Jupyter

00:09:37.159 --> 00:09:43.719
comm and those parameters. And we're able to do pretty complex things in a simple way by using

00:09:43.719 --> 00:09:50.840
classes in Python that ingest this JSON and translate it and put it into these sort of

00:09:50.840 --> 00:10:00.840
templates in Python strings. Same as the filter mask, to do this sorting in Python, it's a method

00:10:00.840 --> 00:10:07.479
chain where we do a dot sort values, and we can pass in a list of column names and a list of

00:10:07.479 --> 00:10:14.359
ascending or descending per column name. This mix of structured information, along with

00:10:15.559 --> 00:10:23.320
string manipulation, allows us to make very rich templates. We're able to test this as well

00:10:23.320 --> 00:10:29.400
by having mock Jupyter comm inputs and making sure that the output is what we would expect.

00:10:29.400 --> 00:10:36.520
Once all of this information is sent through the converter classes in Python, we're able to have

00:10:36.520 --> 00:10:44.679
this beautiful string that users can run out of the box. I'm able to see the type of data frame

00:10:44.679 --> 00:10:50.599
over that Jupyter comm message before I even generate this code. So, I'm only showing users

00:10:50.599 --> 00:10:57.880
the type of code syntax for the data frame library they're using. That's all to say, if you're using

00:10:57.880 --> 00:11:04.039
a data frame that's built in Pandas, you will only be getting Pandas code. If you have a Polars data

00:11:04.039 --> 00:11:09.400
frame, you will only be getting Polars code. There are a few considerations we have to take

00:11:09.400 --> 00:11:17.880
into account. The first one is why not just use AI? I mean, it's 2025, and LLMs can write code.

00:11:18.599 --> 00:11:24.119
But I think the main problem here is that AI is not deterministic. The same input is going to

00:11:24.119 --> 00:11:30.679
produce different outputs, which can be confusing to users. Also, we want guaranteed correctness.

00:11:31.640 --> 00:11:37.000
Because this GUI is fairly simple, we already know all of the types of operations that are

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:42.039
available. We already know the type of column that's available. We can just use these code

00:11:42.039 --> 00:11:47.080
templates to fill in the blanks, and we can make sure that this is correct 100% of the time.

00:11:47.719 --> 00:11:53.960
An LLM might generate code that's mostly right, but using this template, we're able to guarantee

00:11:53.960 --> 00:11:59.559
our output. Speed matters. People don't want to either pay for every single time they want to

00:11:59.719 --> 00:12:04.760
generate this code. It will take longer if you're making these API calls to a different

00:12:05.479 --> 00:12:11.799
LLM that's hosted somewhere else. So, for this, this deterministic rule-based system

00:12:11.799 --> 00:12:15.640
worked really well for this highly structured UI component.

00:12:17.880 --> 00:12:22.520
Now, we can think about, you know, it might be hard once we get into more complex filters.

00:12:23.239 --> 00:12:29.239
There are a few things that really helped out with this. Some of them are on the side of the

00:12:29.479 --> 00:12:36.039
GUI interface. All of the filters in Positron are AND filters, which means that the order doesn't

00:12:36.039 --> 00:12:44.520
matter. So, we can sort for chocolate chip recipes and then see things that are less than 60 minutes

00:12:44.520 --> 00:12:49.320
long or do things in the opposite direction, and it will give the same information.

00:12:51.159 --> 00:12:57.159
This simplifies a lot of our filters. So, perhaps if this continues to build out and

00:12:57.159 --> 00:13:02.440
Positron supports or logic, I'll have to update this code to support the new UI.

00:13:03.479 --> 00:13:07.400
But for now, we don't have to deal with nested filters as much.

00:13:09.320 --> 00:13:14.760
Another thing to think about was what syntax to show. Should we create the most concise code

00:13:14.760 --> 00:13:19.640
or should it be more readable? Do we always want to use method chains or break operations

00:13:19.640 --> 00:13:26.280
up into multiple steps? So, my philosophy when I was building this was that the generated code

00:13:26.280 --> 00:13:30.919
should be idiomatic for each backend. It should look like what an expert would write.

00:13:31.640 --> 00:13:37.159
It could also be a teachable moment so that people can see how to express operations in the code. So,

00:13:37.159 --> 00:13:43.960
we want something that scales well but is also readable. And most crucially, it needs to be copy

00:13:43.960 --> 00:13:50.119
and paste ready. Users should be able to take this code and use it immediately and generate the exact

00:13:50.119 --> 00:13:55.400
same results without any sort of modification. Think of it like writing a recipe. You want it

00:13:55.400 --> 00:14:01.080
to be clear enough that a beginner can follow it but also concise enough that an experienced baker

00:14:01.080 --> 00:14:06.679
doesn't get bored reading it or even make it written in a way that people can modify this

00:14:06.679 --> 00:14:12.760
code easily. Sometimes these goals conflict and we have to make careful choices. The tradeoff

00:14:12.760 --> 00:14:17.799
between ease of use and reproducibility is not fundamental. It's a design choice.

00:14:18.520 --> 00:14:23.960
With thoughtful engineering, we can build tools that are both easy to use and automatically

00:14:23.960 --> 00:14:29.799
reproducible. Users don't always have to remember syntax. They don't always have to take notes about

00:14:29.799 --> 00:14:35.880
what they did. The code is just there, ready to save, share, and rerun. Other type of code

00:14:35.880 --> 00:14:40.440
template scenarios would be really helpful in some Python packages to make things a little bit easier

00:14:40.440 --> 00:14:47.080
to use by automating the easy parts and giving users a template to work off of so that they can

00:14:47.080 --> 00:14:52.359
modify it for themselves later. Thank you so much for joining me on this talk. You can read more

00:14:52.359 --> 00:14:57.799
about Positron at this link. You can find me on my website here and I've also shared with you one

